<sections.2>
Some platelet ±-granule constituents are passively (e.g., immunoglobulins, albumin) or actively (e.g., fibrinogen) taken up from the plasma by receptor-mediated endocytosis; others are synthesized in megakaryocytes (e.g., platelet factor 4, ²-thromboglobulin) and trafficked to the organelle3. n , proteins synthesized in megakaryocytes are markedly reduced, while endocytosed ±-granule constituents are less affected3. his suggests that  megakaryocytes fail to pack their endogeneously synthesized secretory proteins into developing ±-granules.Some platelet Ξ±-granule constituents are passively (e.g., immunoglobulins, albumin) or actively (e.g., fibrinogen) taken up from the plasma by receptor-mediated endocytosis; others are synthesized in megakaryocytes (e.g., platelet factor 4, Ξ²-thromboglobulin) and trafficked to the organelle3. In GPS, proteins synthesized in megakaryocytes are markedly reduced, while endocytosed Ξ±-granule constituents are less affected3. This suggests that GPS megakaryocytes fail to pack their endogeneously synthesized secretory proteins into developing Ξ±-granules.
</sections.2>

